<p>In 1814, as the British burned Washington, commander Sir George Cockburn targeted the offices of the <em>National Intelligencer</em> newspaper, telling his troops, &#8220;Be sure that all the C&#8217;s are destroyed, so that the rascals cannot any longer abuse my name.&#8221;</p>
<p>British politician Thomas Erskine (1750-1823) had such an enormous ego that, it was said, one newspaper had to curtail its coverage because its &#8220;stock of capital I&#8217;s was quite exhausted.&#8221;</p>
